[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1581},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F26\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F26\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F26\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F26\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling\u002F":1558,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F26\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling\u002F":1567},"\u002Fpython\u002F20210926\u002F4028850576\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1540,"date":1541,"description":1542,"extension":1543,"lang":1544,"meta":1545,"navigation":59,"path":1546,"readingMinutes":1547,"seo":1548,"standalone":1549,"stem":1550,"tags":1551,"tldr":1555,"updated":1541,"url":1556,"__hash__":1557},"content\u002Fen\u002FPython\u002Fpython-25-exception-handling.md","Learning Python From a JavaScript Angle (25) - Exception Handling","1002526164",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1529},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,43,155,165,172,175,179,182,217,224,230,233,236,282,288,292,305,358,369,380,474,477,483,486,492,684,706,870,876,885,1044,1050,1055,1114,1120,1126,1130,1151,1157,1359,1379,1388,1391,1445,1453,1456,1460,1463,1467,1483,1487,1519,1525],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Next up is something really, really important: handling errors. The technique for this is usually called exception handling.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"the-idea-behind-exception-handling","The Idea Behind Exception Handling",[17,25,26],{},"Let's start with what exception handling even is. When you're building a system, you're bound to run into error situations. The user's network is flaky, they type in the wrong data, you forget to declare a variable, a typhoon snaps the power line mid-input and the power goes out, or the kid next door cuts your network cable while you're online (a friend actually told me his network cable got cut by a neighborhood kid). If you don't put some error-handling defenses in place, your system is going to lose your users' trust the moment it goes live. So handling errors properly really matters.",[17,28,29,30,34,35,38,39,42],{},"To avoid these situations we usually reach for exception handling. If you've already started writing ES7 syntax, you're probably very familiar with ",[31,32,33],"code",{},"async"," and ",[31,36,37],{},"await",", and you've definitely used ",[31,40,41],{},"try...catch",". Here's a quick snippet:",[44,45,50],"pre",{"className":46,"code":47,"language":48,"meta":49,"style":49},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","\nasync function getData () {\n  try{\n    const res = await axios.get('xxxx');\n  } catch (error) {\n    console.error(error);\n  }\n}\n","js","",[31,51,52,61,78,87,119,131,143,149],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,54,57],"span",{"class":55,"line":56},"line",1,[53,58,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},true,"\n",[53,62,64,67,70,74],{"class":55,"line":63},2,[53,65,33],{"class":66},"sWyjQ",[53,68,69],{"class":66}," function",[53,71,73],{"class":72},"sj_SG"," getData",[53,75,77],{"class":76},"sMAXC"," () {\n",[53,79,81,84],{"class":55,"line":80},3,[53,82,83],{"class":66},"  try",[53,85,86],{"class":76},"{\n",[53,88,90,93,97,100,103,106,109,112,116],{"class":55,"line":89},4,[53,91,92],{"class":66},"    const",[53,94,96],{"class":95},"sCcAr"," res",[53,98,99],{"class":66}," =",[53,101,102],{"class":66}," await",[53,104,105],{"class":76}," axios.",[53,107,108],{"class":72},"get",[53,110,111],{"class":76},"(",[53,113,115],{"class":114},"sTRMh","'xxxx'",[53,117,118],{"class":76},");\n",[53,120,122,125,128],{"class":55,"line":121},5,[53,123,124],{"class":76},"  } ",[53,126,127],{"class":66},"catch",[53,129,130],{"class":76}," (error) {\n",[53,132,134,137,140],{"class":55,"line":133},6,[53,135,136],{"class":76},"    console.",[53,138,139],{"class":72},"error",[53,141,142],{"class":76},"(error);\n",[53,144,146],{"class":55,"line":145},7,[53,147,148],{"class":76},"  }\n",[53,150,152],{"class":55,"line":151},8,[53,153,154],{"class":76},"}\n",[17,156,157,158,160,161,164],{},"In short, when the AJAX request fails unexpectedly or the network drops, it'll automatically jump to the ",[31,159,127],{}," block. One thing to watch out for though: if this is front-end code that an end user sees, don't use ",[31,162,163],{},"console.log"," as your error message, because a regular user has no idea what dev tools (devtools) even are. So this is just example code.",[17,166,167],{},[168,169],"img",{"alt":170,"src":171},"A user who has no idea why the system broke","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002F%E6%88%91%E7%9A%84%E6%A2%97%E5%9C%96%E5%89%B5%E4%BD%9C-1631979362.png",[17,173,174],{},"That's a simple bit of exception handling. Now let's hop over to Python and see how exception handling is written there.",[12,176,178],{"id":177},"exception-handling","Exception Handling",[17,180,181],{},"First let's deliberately cause an error:",[44,183,187],{"className":184,"code":185,"language":186,"meta":49,"style":49},"language-py shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","def sayHello():\n  print('Hello')\n\nprint(myName)\n\nsayHello()\n","py",[31,188,189,194,199,203,208,212],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,190,191],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,192,193],{},"def sayHello():\n",[53,195,196],{"class":55,"line":63},[53,197,198],{},"  print('Hello')\n",[53,200,201],{"class":55,"line":80},[53,202,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,204,205],{"class":55,"line":89},[53,206,207],{},"print(myName)\n",[53,209,210],{"class":55,"line":121},[53,211,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,213,214],{"class":55,"line":133},[53,215,216],{},"sayHello()\n",[17,218,219,220,223],{},"The code above looks totally fine, right? But running it actually throws ",[31,221,222],{},"NameError: name 'myName' is not defined",".",[17,225,226],{},[168,227],{"alt":228,"src":229},"Scared speechless","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002F1631980095440.png",[17,231,232],{},"Oh, and if you're asking me why this error shows up, I'm sending you back to re-read the chapter \"Learning Python From a JavaScript Angle (4) - Types and Variables\", because I explained it there.",[17,234,235],{},"Now if you wrap this in exception handling, you can stop the code from breaking on the error, which lets the rest of the code keep running:",[44,237,239],{"className":184,"code":238,"language":186,"meta":49,"style":49},"def sayHello():\n  print('Hello')\n\ntry:\n  print(myName)\nexcept:\n  print('You forgot to declare the variable.')\n\nsayHello()\n",[31,240,241,245,249,253,258,263,268,273,277],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,242,243],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,244,193],{},[53,246,247],{"class":55,"line":63},[53,248,198],{},[53,250,251],{"class":55,"line":80},[53,252,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,254,255],{"class":55,"line":89},[53,256,257],{},"try:\n",[53,259,260],{"class":55,"line":121},[53,261,262],{},"  print(myName)\n",[53,264,265],{"class":55,"line":133},[53,266,267],{},"except:\n",[53,269,270],{"class":55,"line":145},[53,271,272],{},"  print('You forgot to declare the variable.')\n",[53,274,275],{"class":55,"line":151},[53,276,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,278,280],{"class":55,"line":279},9,[53,281,216],{},[17,283,284],{},[168,285],{"alt":286,"src":287},"Zenitsu finally getting the value of exception handling","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Fother\u002F%E6%88%91%E7%9A%84%E6%A2%97%E5%9C%96%E5%89%B5%E4%BD%9C-1631980482.png",[12,289,291],{"id":290},"exception-handling-for-specific-error-types","Exception Handling for Specific Error Types",[17,293,294,295,297,298,301,302,304],{},"On top of that, you can also handle specific error types. What does that mean? Take the earlier example: it throws ",[31,296,222],{},", and the error type there is ",[31,299,300],{},"NameError",". So you can write a custom handler specifically for ",[31,303,300],{},":",[44,306,308],{"className":184,"code":307,"language":186,"meta":49,"style":49},"def sayHello():\n  print('Hello')\n\ntry:\n  print(myName)\nexcept NameError:\n  print('You forgot to declare the variable.')\nexcept:\n  print('Just a plain error.')\n\nsayHello()\n",[31,309,310,314,318,322,326,330,335,339,343,348,353],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,311,312],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,313,193],{},[53,315,316],{"class":55,"line":63},[53,317,198],{},[53,319,320],{"class":55,"line":80},[53,321,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,323,324],{"class":55,"line":89},[53,325,257],{},[53,327,328],{"class":55,"line":121},[53,329,262],{},[53,331,332],{"class":55,"line":133},[53,333,334],{},"except NameError:\n",[53,336,337],{"class":55,"line":145},[53,338,272],{},[53,340,341],{"class":55,"line":151},[53,342,267],{},[53,344,345],{"class":55,"line":279},[53,346,347],{},"  print('Just a plain error.')\n",[53,349,351],{"class":55,"line":350},10,[53,352,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,354,356],{"class":55,"line":355},11,[53,357,216],{},[17,359,360,361,368],{},"There are a ton of error types out there, so I'd recommend reading ",[362,363,367],"a",{"href":364,"rel":365},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.w3schools.com\u002FPYTHON\u002Fpython_ref_exceptions.asp",[366],"nofollow","this page"," to see what common ones exist.",[17,370,371,372,375,376,379],{},"So does JavaScript have something like type-specific exception handling? Basically yes, the syntax is just a bit different. In JavaScript you have to use ",[31,373,374],{},"instanceof"," to check the error type. For example, accessing a variable you never declared throws a ",[31,377,378],{},"ReferenceError",", so it'd look like this:",[44,381,383],{"className":46,"code":382,"language":48,"meta":49,"style":49},"try {\n  console.log(Ray); \u002F\u002F undeclared variable, throws \"Uncaught ReferenceError: Ray is not defined\"\n} catch(error) {\n  if(error instanceof ReferenceError) {\n    console.log('You accessed a variable that does not exist');\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log('The code keeps running just fine');\n",[31,384,385,393,408,418,435,448,452,456,460],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,386,387,390],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,388,389],{"class":66},"try",[53,391,392],{"class":76}," {\n",[53,394,395,398,401,404],{"class":55,"line":63},[53,396,397],{"class":76},"  console.",[53,399,400],{"class":72},"log",[53,402,403],{"class":76},"(Ray); ",[53,405,407],{"class":406},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F undeclared variable, throws \"Uncaught ReferenceError: Ray is not defined\"\n",[53,409,410,413,415],{"class":55,"line":80},[53,411,412],{"class":76},"} ",[53,414,127],{"class":66},[53,416,417],{"class":76},"(error) {\n",[53,419,420,423,426,428,432],{"class":55,"line":89},[53,421,422],{"class":66},"  if",[53,424,425],{"class":76},"(error ",[53,427,374],{"class":66},[53,429,431],{"class":430},"s_sBn"," ReferenceError",[53,433,434],{"class":76},") {\n",[53,436,437,439,441,443,446],{"class":55,"line":121},[53,438,136],{"class":76},[53,440,400],{"class":72},[53,442,111],{"class":76},[53,444,445],{"class":114},"'You accessed a variable that does not exist'",[53,447,118],{"class":76},[53,449,450],{"class":55,"line":133},[53,451,148],{"class":76},[53,453,454],{"class":55,"line":145},[53,455,154],{"class":76},[53,457,458],{"class":55,"line":151},[53,459,60],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":59},[53,461,462,465,467,469,472],{"class":55,"line":279},[53,463,464],{"class":76},"console.",[53,466,400],{"class":72},[53,468,111],{"class":76},[53,470,471],{"class":114},"'The code keeps running just fine'",[53,473,118],{"class":76},[17,475,476],{},"So out of those two, which one do you like more?",[17,478,479],{},[168,480],{"alt":481,"src":482},"I want them all","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1632036275949.png",[12,484,485],{"id":485},"finally",[17,487,488,489,491],{},"There's another piece called ",[31,490,485],{},". You see it most often when you need to do something specific after asking a remote server for data. For example, when writing Vue we usually use a loading library to cover the wait time during an AJAX request, which improves the user experience as much as possible. Here's a common but not-great way to write it:",[44,493,495],{"className":46,"code":494,"language":48,"meta":49,"style":49},"const app = {\n  data() {\n    return {\n      isLoading: false,\n    };\n  },\n  methods:{\n    async getData() {\n      try {\n        this.isLoading = true;\n        await axios.get('xxxxx');\n        this.isLoading = false;\n      } catch (error) {\n        console.log(error)\n      }\n    },\n  },\n};\n\nVue.createApp(app).mount('#app');\n",[31,496,497,509,517,524,535,540,545,550,559,566,583,599,613,623,634,640,646,651,657,662],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,498,499,502,505,507],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,500,501],{"class":66},"const",[53,503,504],{"class":95}," app",[53,506,99],{"class":66},[53,508,392],{"class":76},[53,510,511,514],{"class":55,"line":63},[53,512,513],{"class":72},"  data",[53,515,516],{"class":76},"() {\n",[53,518,519,522],{"class":55,"line":80},[53,520,521],{"class":66},"    return",[53,523,392],{"class":76},[53,525,526,529,532],{"class":55,"line":89},[53,527,528],{"class":76},"      isLoading: ",[53,530,531],{"class":95},"false",[53,533,534],{"class":76},",\n",[53,536,537],{"class":55,"line":121},[53,538,539],{"class":76},"    };\n",[53,541,542],{"class":55,"line":133},[53,543,544],{"class":76},"  },\n",[53,546,547],{"class":55,"line":145},[53,548,549],{"class":76},"  methods:{\n",[53,551,552,555,557],{"class":55,"line":151},[53,553,554],{"class":66},"    async",[53,556,73],{"class":72},[53,558,516],{"class":76},[53,560,561,564],{"class":55,"line":279},[53,562,563],{"class":66},"      try",[53,565,392],{"class":76},[53,567,568,571,574,577,580],{"class":55,"line":350},[53,569,570],{"class":95},"        this",[53,572,573],{"class":76},".isLoading ",[53,575,576],{"class":66},"=",[