7,1121,1122],{},[168,1123],{"alt":1124,"src":1125},"Did you get it?","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1632036811025.png",[12,1127,1129],{"id":1128},"throwing-raise","Throwing (raise)",[17,1131,1132,1133,1136,1137,1140,1141,1144,1145,1147,1148,1150],{},"The clever ones among you probably immediately thought of JavaScript's ",[31,1134,1135],{},"throw",". Here's a special case. When we do AJAX create\u002Fupdate\u002Fdelete operations, the back end might not return the matching HTTP status code. Instead it might hand you a ",[31,1138,1139],{},"status"," field to tell you whether this insert came back ",[31,1142,1143],{},"true"," or ",[31,1146,531],{},", so this is when we use ",[31,1149,1135],{}," to kick the current state out to the exception handler.",[17,1152,1153,1154,1156],{},"Why does this happen? If the back end always returns a 200 no matter what, then AJAX will of course think the request succeeded and treat it as a non-failure, so it won't go into ",[31,1155,127],{},". From a JavaScript angle, we might write it like this:",[44,1158,1160],{"className":46,"code":1159,"language":48,"meta":49,"style":49},"const app = {\n  data() {\n    return {\n      isLoading: false,\n    };\n  },\n  methods:{\n    async getData() {\n      try {\n        this.isLoading = true;\n        const res = await axios.get('xxxxx');\n        if(!res.data.status) {\n          throw Error('Error');\n        }\n      } catch (error) {\n        console.log(error)\n      } finally {\n        this.isLoading = false;\n      }\n    },\n  },\n};\n\nVue.createApp(app).mount('#app');\n",[31,1161,1162,1172,1178,1184,1192,1196,1200,1204,1212,1218,1230,1251,1264,1279,1284,1292,1300,1308,1320,1324,1328,1332,1337,1342],{"__ignoreMap":49},[53,1163,1164,1166,1168,1170],{"class":55,"line":56},[53,1165,501],{"class":66},[53,1167,504],{"class":95},[53,1169,99],{"class":66},[53,1171,392],{"class":76},[5